    "jays": {
      "full_name": "Toronto Blue Jays",
      "league": "MLB",
      "record": "13-16",
      "detail": "4th in AL East",
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Jays",
        "body": "Trey Yesavage stormed back from World Series glory like a man possessed, firing 5.1 shutout innings in <strong>the Blue Jays' 3-0 blanking of the Red Sox</strong> last night - his first start since hoisting that trophy in '25, no walks, just four hits and three K's to snap Boston's skid and even the series. At 13-16, fourth in the AL East and 6.5 back, Toronto's clinging to their wild-card pulse on a one-game streak after splitting four with Cleveland; Vladimir Guerrero Jr. delivered the dagger with a two-out single scoring Miles Shaw, all three runs plating in clutch spots against a Red Sox staff that couldn't breathe. No major injuries clouding the clubhouse - Eloy Jimenez is steady at.696 OPS since his call-up - but this early swoon demands proof they're not fading into divisional irrelevance. <strong>Eric Lauer takes the hill this afternoon at 2:07 for a series clincher</strong>; win it, and the trajectory bends toward contender talk - lose, and the ghosts of too many Aprils past grow louder.",
        "updated": "Updated April 29, 2026"
      },
